                     <gram type="num">pl.</gram>
                  </gramGrp>
               </form>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="qolase-ys-1">
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>a woman’s headgear</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example" xml:lang="jpa">
                  <quote>ויעשו להם חגורות. חגורה אין כת' כאן, אלא חגורות - אסטכיון, טלין, סדינין. ולאשה ציצלין, דקיסלוון [*קולוסין], סבכיון.</quote>
                  <bibl>
                     <ref type="witness">Yalq 27</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">I 93: 44</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa">סבכיון</ref>
                  <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa">אסטכיון</ref>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>And they made themeselves girdles (ḥagorot). R. Abba b. Kahana said: Not hagorah (a girdle) but hagorot is written: now hagorot implies shirts, robes, and linen cloaks; and just as these are made for man, so for woman are made girdles, hats, and hair nets. (Cf. Freedman / Simon I 152-153)</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <note>= <bibl type="ancient">GenR 19,6 [I 176: 1]</bibl></note>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <note>Spelling in Yalqut is corrupted. Etymology obscure, cf. GenR <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa">קולסי</ref>.</note>
            <ref type="bibliography">
               <bibl>
                  <title>Sokoloff, DJPA</title>
                  <citedRange>546b</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </ref>
         </entry>
